==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Scheme
<hw>Scheme</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[L. <ets>schema</ets> a
rhetorical figure, a shape, figure, manner, Gr. <?/, <?/, form, shape,
outline, plan, fr. <?/, <?/, to have or hold, to hold out, sustain,
check, stop; cf. Skr. <ets>sah</ets> to be victorious, to endure, to
hold out, AS. <ets>sige</ets> victory, G. <ets>sieg</ets>.
<ets>Cf</ets>. <er>Epoch</er>, <er>Hectic</er>, <er>School</er>.]</ety>
<sn>1.</sn> <def>A combination of things connected and adjusted by
design; a system.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The appearance and outward <qex>scheme</qex> of things.</q>
<rj><qau>Locke.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Such a <qex>scheme</qex> of things as shall at once take in time
and eternity.</q> <rj><qau>Atterbury.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Arguments . . . sufficient to support and demonstrate a whole
<qex>scheme</qex> of moral philosophy.</q> <rj><qau>J.
Edwards.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The Revolution came and changed his whole <qex>scheme</qex> of
life.</q> <rj><qau>Macaulay.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A plan or theory something to be done; a design; a
project; <as>as, to form a <ex>scheme</ex></as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The stoical <qex>scheme</qex> of supplying our wants by lopping
off our desires, is like cutting off our feet when we want shoes.</q>
<rj><qau>Swift.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>Any lineal or mathematical diagram; an
outline.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>To draw an exact <qex>scheme</qex> of Constantinople, or a map of
France.</q> <rj><qau>South.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <fld>(Astrol.)</fld> <def>A representation of the aspects
of the celestial bodies for any moment or at a given event.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>A blue silk case, from which was drawn a <qex>scheme</qex> of
nativity.</q> <rj><qau>Sir W. Scott.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- Plan; project; contrivance; purpose; device;
plot.</syn> -- <usage><er>Scheme</er>, <er>Plan</er>. <xex>Scheme</xex>
and <xex>plan</xex> are subordinate to <xex>design</xex>; they propose
modes of carrying our designs into effect. <xex>Scheme</xex> is the
least definite of the two, and lies more in speculation. A
<xex>plan</xex> is drawn out into details with a view to being carried
into effect. As <xex>schemes</xex> are speculative, they often prove
visionary; hence the opprobrious use of the words <xex>schemer</xex> and
<xex>scheming</xex>. <xex>Plans</xex>, being more practical, are more
frequently carried into effect.</usage>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>He forms the well-concerted <qex>scheme</qex> of mischief;⟦br⟧
'T is fixed, 't is done, and both are doomed to death.</q>
<rj><qau>Rowe.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Artists and <qex>plans</qex> relieved my solemn hours;⟦br⟧
I founded palaces, and planted bowers.</q>
<rj><qau>Prior.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Scheme</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Scheme
<hw>Scheme</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos>
<conjf>Schemed</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Scheming</conjf>.]</vmorph> <def>To make a scheme of; to plan; to
design; to project; to plot.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>That wickedness which <qex>schemed</qex>, and executed, his
destruction.</q> <rj><qau>G. Stuart.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Scheme</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Scheme
<hw>Scheme</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <def>To form a scheme or
schemes.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Schemeful</ent>⟦br⟧
